    <title>GM challenges Trump administration to start a nationwide zero-emissions vehicle program</title>
    <content type="html">  
    &lt;img alt="" src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/Ood-JOvUej1rh9X5mzWi30tOo6Y=/0x0:2040x1360/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/61920341/akrales_170405_1582_0603.0.0.jpg" /&gt;



  &lt;p id="IrCaOU"&gt;General Motors is &lt;a href="https://media.gm.com/media/us/en/gm/news.detail.html/content/Pages/news/us/en/2018/oct/1026-emissions.html"&gt;advocating&lt;/a&gt; for a new nationwide program that promotes electric cars and other zero-emissions vehicles. The so-called “National Zero Emission Vehicle (NZEV) program” would potentially put 7 million “long-range” EVs on the road by 2030 and reduce CO2 emissions by 375 million tons. GM is also calling for more investment into electric charging infrastructure, and it’s encouraging the government to support EV and battery technology in order to keep pace with countries like China.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="F5vZcE"&gt;To do this, GM is calling for 25 percent of all automakers’ fleets to switch to electric or hybrid power. It also suggests an expansion of California’s current zero-emissions vehicle (ZEV) “credit” system in which automakers have to make and sell a...&lt;/p&gt;
